} else {
    System.out.println("Strings are different objects");
}

if (s1.equals(s2)) {
    System.out.println("Strings have the same value");
} else {
    System.out.println("Strings have different values");
}
```

In this example, `s1` and `s2` are different objects, but they have the same value. `s1 == s2` returns `false`, but `s1.equals(s2)` returns `true`.

### Conclusion
- **Use `==` to compare references**: This is useful for checking if two strings are the same object.
- **Use `equals()` to compare values**: This is useful for checking if two strings have the same value.

Always be mindful of the context in which you are comparing strings to ensure you are using the correct operator.

